SYPHILIS - USA (05): (ARIZONA) CONGENITAL, INCREASING INCIDENCE, INCARCERATION, DRUG USE, HOMELESSNESS
******************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Thu 18 Nov 2021 14:22 MST
Source: KGUN [edited]
https://www.kgun9.com/news/local-news/public-health-alert-syphilis-is-on-the-rise-in-pima-county


Syphilis is on the rise in Pima County [AZ]. As of October 2021, 133 female cases have been reported; 25 of those involved pregnancy. Taking a look at 2020 for comparison, a total of 131 cases were reported among females; 27 of those patients reported being pregnant.

The factors that go into the high rates, according to the Pima County Health Department [see below], include incarceration, reinfection, drug use, and homelessness during pregnancy. Those are the primary reasons for infections among congenital syphilis mothers and heterosexual men.

According to the CDC, men account for the most cases of syphilis (https://www.cdc.gov/std/statistics/2019/figures/SYPH-2.htm).

Syphilis is a sexually transmitted disease that can be cured with the right treatment. Symptoms may include a painless sore that appears inside or near the mouth, genital or anus, or a rash that appears on the palms of hands, bottom of feet, or on the body between the armpits and upper thighs.

Information and confidential testing [are] available Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. at several local clinics, and walk-ins are welcome [Pima County Health Department].

[Byline: Martha Serda]

