[Pima County (population 980 263 in 2010) is in the south-central region of the US state of Arizona; its county seat is the city of Tucson (population 535 677 in 2017), where most of the population resides (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pima_County,_Arizona). Arizona is one of the southwestern states, which include California, Arizona, New Mexico, and Texas, that border Mexico. A map showing the location of Pima County can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Pima+County,+AZ.

In the United States, the number of reported cases of primary and secondary syphilis among women and the number of reported cases of congenital syphilis have increased every year since 2012. Arizona ranks next to the highest among US states for congenital syphilis in 2019, with 133.1 cases of congenital syphilis per 100 000 live births (https://www.cdc.gov/std/statistics/2019/tables/40.htm). The other states with rates of congenital syphilis above the national average (48.5 cases per 100 000) in 2019 are in the South and Southwest, including Texas (138.2), New Mexico (117.8), Nevada (114.7), Louisiana (111.4), California (94.3), Oklahoma (85.6), Florida (64.8), and Arkansas (56.0).

As stated in both items above, a history of incarceration, reinfection, drug use, and homelessness during pregnancy are prominent themes among congenital syphilis mothers and heterosexual men in Pima County. - Mod.ML

